continuous jobs -
        - refers to jobs that run streaming workloads continuosly rather than batch mode
        - runs non stop, processing data as it arrive
        - used when we are working with streaming data
    eg
        -ingesting streaming data from kafka

conditional execution - 
        - helps to build dependency chain b/w tasks based on condition
        available conditions are
            - all succeeded - alteast one successed - none failed - all done - alteast one failed - all failed
        
Job parameters - 
        parameters that we pass for each task
        for notebook - key value pair 
        for python script - array of string

Job contexts - 
        special set of parameters that provides metadata information of the jobs/tasks - like task_id etc

Task values - 
        - used to pass parameters b/w tasks
        - we can set parameter value on one task and which can be used in subsequently referenced tasks=  as be did in flexflow

Late jobs - 
        - usually no one will keep on monitor the jobs runs, if it runs more then usual time then we use soft timeout after which they receive a warning that a job or task run is taking longer then expected time

run as service principle- 
        by default, job run as the identity of the job owner, we need to change into service prinicple - 
        then job get the permissions set to service principle instead of owner

job schedule options - 
        1. scheduled - add a time when job need to be triggered
        2. continous - when the job sucessful or failed, job will triggered again in 1min 
        3. file arrival - we need to specify the location, if any file arrived into that location job get triggered

to set job parameters - 
for python scripts - 
        ["{{job.parameters.param_dict}}","{{job.run_id}}"]
for notebook - 
        key             value
        task_name       {{task.name}}
        run_id          {{task.run_id}}

to pull job param values
in python scripts 
        import sys, json
        param_dict = json.loads(sys.argv[1])
in notebook
        task_name = dbutils.widgets.get("task_name")

to define parameters from one task to other
set - dbutils.jobs.taskValues.set(key="data_dict",value= dict)
pull - data_dict = dbutils.jobs.taskvalues.get(taskey="pre_processing",key="data_dict")

to pull this in job task condition
{{tasks.pre_processing.values.data_dict}}

